<p>Another approach relevant to the 3D case was considered in reference [
 <xref rid="B31-materials-12-03464" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>], where AXCCA was used to reconstruct the orientational correlation function 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm207">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">Θ</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>r</mi>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msup>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>′</mo>
       </msup>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mi>θ</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. This function determines the probability to find in the system two bonds of length 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm208">
   <mrow>
    <mi>r</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm209">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msup>
      <mi>r</mi>
      <mo>′</mo>
     </msup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> with an angle 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm210">
   <mrow>
    <mi>θ</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> between them. It has been theoretically shown that by measuring a large number (&gt;
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm211">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msup>
      <mrow>
       <mn>10</mn>
      </mrow>
      <mn>5</mn>
     </msup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) of anisotropic diffraction patterns from liquid phases, metallic glasses, or organic molecules, one can in principle reconstruct the function 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm212">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi mathvariant="sans-serif">Θ</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>r</mi>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <msup>
        <mi>r</mi>
        <mo>′</mo>
       </msup>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mi>θ</mi>
      </mrow>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>.
</p>
